Comparative Analysis of Statistical Learning Techniques in Tumor classification

Michael Nichols and John Lee

2023-12-08

Introduction

Breast cancer is the most prevalent form of cancer among women world wide. Current research is focused on early detection of breast cancer as it is the most effective way to significantly improve survival rates. Recent advances in science and machines learning offer promising results in the evaluation of the stage of the tumor and its progression in order to determine the optimal treatment.

This paper presents a comprehensive analysis of various statistical learning techniques applied to the classification of benign and malignant tumors. The diagnosis of tumors as benign of malignant is critical in determining the best treatment and prognosis. Statistical methods offer significant advantages to predict whether a tumor is benign or malignant by leveraging large data sets to make accurate predictions. The data used for this is from the Wisconsin Diagnostic Breast Cancer (WDBC) data set. Various statistical learning procedures were used for prediction.

This data sets consists of 569 samples with 32 features that accompany every sample. Of the samples 357 are benign and 212 are malignant tumors. This studys primary challenge is determining whether a certain tissue sample is malignant or benign based off the 32 diagnostic features. Many different statistical learning techniques could be used for classification but this study only considers linear regression, logistic regression, linear discriminant analysis, quadratic discriminant analysis, naive bayes, K-nearest neighbors, best subset selection, forward step-wise selection, backward step-wise selection, ridge regression, the lasso, and tree-based methods (classification trees, bagging, and random forests).

Feature Information

  1. ID = ID number
  2. Diagnosis (M=malignant, B=benign)
  3. Radius (mean of the distance from center to points on the perimeter)
  4. Texture (standard deviation of gray-scale values)
  5. Perimeter
  6. Area
  7. Smoothness (local variation in radius lengths)
  8. Compactness (perimeter^2 / area 1.0)
  9. Concavity (severity of concave portions of the contour)
  10. Concave points (number of concave portions of the contour)
  11. Symmetry
  12. Fractal dimension (coastline approximation -1 )

All varialbes except for concavity_mean are significant at the 5% level. Now, we predict the probability that a tumor is benign or malignant on the training data

glm.probs <- predict(glm.fit, type = "response")
glm.prob.logit <- predict (glm.fit)

#create a vector of class predictions based on whether the predicted probability of a malignant tumor is greater than or less than 0.5
glm.pred <- rep("0", 569)
glm.pred[glm.probs >.5] = "1"

#confusion matrix
table(glm.pred, data$diagnosis)
##         
## glm.pred   0   1
##        0  68 155
##        1 289  57
mean(glm.pred == data$diagnosis)
## [1] 0.2196837

57+68/569=.2196 or 21.96% correctly predicted. Our model at its current stage is worse than random guessing and this is on the training set. We have a training error rate of 78.04%. The confusion matrix is showing us how often our classififer makes errors, that is, false positives or false negatives. Our sensitivity is 26.87% and our specificity is 80.95%. Additionally, a simple but useless classifier that always predicts an malignant tumor will have an error rate of 62.74%. In other words, the trivial null classifier will achieve an error rate that is lower than the training set error rate modeled by the logistic regression which is not good.

Lets modify the threshold for classification. We want to be conservative in our predictions of individuals who have malignant tumors, while still to be avoided, an incorrect classificatioin of a benign tumor as malignant is less important. Upon looking at the predictions, most are very close to 0 (10^-15) or very close to 1 so this is where we set our threshold.

glm.pred2 <- rep("0", 569)
glm.pred2[glm.probs >.00000000001] = "1"

#confusion matrix
table(glm.pred2, data$diagnosis)
##          
## glm.pred2   0   1
##         0  62 155
##         1 295  57
mean(glm.pred2 == data$diagnosis)
## [1] 0.2091388

57+62/569=.2091 or 20.91% correctly predicted. This lowered threshold actually performs worse than the previous which was not expected. This may because we are trying to predict a binary response using multiple highly correlated predictors. For example, a mass with a large mean perimeter likely has a large mean area. However, these results are more likely due to the assumption that there is a linear relationship between the log odds and the predictors thus I will explore feature selection, regularization, and decision trees later on.

Now we create random training and test sets (chose to split the data at the 3rd quartile of the most highly correlated variable with diagnosis) using the validation set approach for an estimate of the test error rate. We do this for Logistic Regression, LDA, QDA, KNN, and Naive Bayes. We are not concerned with an estimate of the training error rate. We want to create a model that performs well on a new independent data point rather than a model that performs well on a observations that was used to train the model. For the rest of this study, we will focus on test error rates.

set.seed(1)
train <- (data$concave.points_worst < 0.16140)
test <- data[!train,]
test_diagnosis <- data$diagnosis[!train]
dim(test)
## [1] 143  32
#fit logistic regression model using only training set
glm.fit2 <- glm(diagnosis ~ . -id, data = data, family = binomial, subset = train)
glm.probs2 <- predict(glm.fit2, test, type = "response")
glm.pred3 <- rep("0",143)
glm.pred3[glm.probs2 >.5] <- "1"
table(glm.pred3, test_diagnosis)

We were very skeptical of the test error estimates obtained above (validatioin set approach) so we proceeded with leave out out cross validation (LOOCV) to verify the test error estimates. We did this beucase we got very low test error rates when our training error rates were very high so eliminating the randomness, through LOOCV, in the split of the data would yield more trustworthy results.

Leave One Out Cross Validation

Logistic regression

errors <- rep(0, nrow(data))
for (i in 1:nrow(data)) {
  glm.log <- glm(diagnosis ~ . -id, data = data[-i, ], family = binomial)
  
  glm.problog <- predict(glm.log, newdata = data[i, ], type = "response") 
  
  errors[i] <- (glm.problog > 0.5) != (data$diagnosis[i] == "1")
}
loocv_error <- mean(errors)
loocv_error
## [1] 0.3427065

LOOCV test error estimate for Logistic regression: 0.3427065

We determined that the optimal model is most likely LDA through analysis of the test error rates but we can now use K-fold cross validation to iterate over all the model and plot them against each other to obtain a result that is less biased.

K-fold CV for determination of optimal model (generative models for classification)

data$diagnosis <- as.factor(data$diagnosis) # ensure diagnosis is a factor
data <- data[, -which(names(data) == "id")]

# Define a control function for 10-fold cross-validation
control <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)

# Set up a list to store models
models <- list()

# Logistic Regression
set.seed(1)
models$logistic <- train(diagnosis ~ ., data = data, method = "glm", family = "binomial", trControl = control)

# LDA
set.seed(1)
models$lda <- train(diagnosis ~ ., data = data, method = "lda", trControl = control)

# QDA
set.seed(1)
models$qda <- train(diagnosis ~ ., data = data, method = "qda", trControl = control)

# KNN (tuning for the best k)
set.seed(1)
knnGrid <- expand.grid(.k = 1:20) #k from 1 to 20
models$knn <- train(diagnosis ~ ., data = data, method = "knn", tuneGrid = knnGrid, trControl = control)

# Naive Bayes
set.seed(1)
models$naivebayes <- train(diagnosis ~ ., data = data, method = "naive_bayes", trControl = control)

# Review the results
results <- resamples(models)
summary(results)

Bootstrap for classification accuracy (for LDA and QDA)

LDA

set.seed(1)
bootstrap_lda <- function(data, indices) {
  boot_data <- data[indices, ] 
  test_data <- data[-indices, ] 
  fit <- lda(diagnosis ~ ., data = boot_data)
  predictions <- predict(fit, test_data)$class
  accuracy <- mean(predictions == test_data$diagnosis)
  return(accuracy)
}

results <- boot(data = data, statistic = bootstrap_lda, R = 1000)

boot_mean_accuracy_lda <- mean(results$t)
boot_se_accuracy_lda <- sd(results$t)

boot_mean_accuracy_lda
## [1] 0.9529731
boot_se_accuracy_lda
## [1] 0.01404106

We accurately classify about 95.30% of cases over 1000 bootstrap samples. We also have low SE relative to accuracy indicating the the model performance is quite stable

The best 1 variable model uses concave.points_worst. The best 2 variable model uses concave.points_worst and radius_worst. The best 5 variable model uses area_worst, radius_worst, texture_worst, concave.points_mean, and perimeter_mean. This highlights how best subset selected each additional variable subject to the greatest reduction in RSS. Though concave.points_worst was the best variable that captured the most amount of variation in diagnosis, when more predictors are added we see in the 5 variable model that it does not include this varialbe.

We plot RSS, adjusted R^2, C_p, and BIC at once to pick the best model. We was a high adjusted R^2, low Cp, and low BIC. The maximums/minimums are pointed out on the graph to show a visual representation of the optimal model flexibility.

par(mfrow=c(2,2))

#RSS graph 
plot(reg.summary$rss, xlab = "Number of Variables", ylab = "RSS", type = "l")

#adjusted R^2 graph
plot(reg.summary$adjr2, xlab = "Number of Variables",
     ylab = "Adjusted RSq", type = "l")

#We can use the points() function to put points on an already created plot, instead of a new plot. The which.max() function will identify the maximum point of a vector for us. We will use them together to mark the point with the largest adjusted R^2, smallest Cp, and smallest BIC

which.max(reg.summary$adjr2)
## [1] 14
points(14, reg.summary$adjr2[14], col = "red", cex = 2, pch=20)

#Cp graph
plot(reg.summary$cp, xlab = "Number of Variables",
     ylab = "Cp", type = "l")
which.min(reg.summary$cp)
## [1] 14
points(14, reg.summary$cp[14], col = "red", cex = 2, pch=20)

#BIC graph
plot(reg.summary$bic, xlab = "Number of Variables",
     ylab = "BIC", type = "l")
which.min(reg.summary$bic)
## [1] 11
points(11, reg.summary$bic[11], col = "red", cex = 2, pch=20)

reg.summary$adjr2[11]
## [1] 0.762951

The 11 variable model has the lowest BIC and all other models have higher degrees of freedom so we determine that the 11 variable model is the best one chosen through best subset selection. This 11 variable model still captures 76.30% of the variation in diagnosis which is not bad prediction but must also take into account the huge reduction of bias by only using 11/29 of the predictors.

The best 1 variable model uses concave.points_worst like best subset. The best 2 variable model uses concave.points_worst and radius_worst like best subset. The best 5 variable model uses concave.points_worst, radius_worst, smoothness_se, texture_worst, and area_worst which is a little different from the best subset 5 variable model. This is a characteristic of forward step-wise selection in that variables selected in earlier stages necessarily must be included in later models unlike best subset.

We plot RSS, adjusted R^2, C_p, and BIC at once to pick the best model. We was a high adjusted R^2, low Cp, and low BIC. The maximums/minimums are pointed out on the graph to show a visual representation of the optimal model flexibility.

par(mfrow=c(2,2))

#RSS graph
plot(reg.summary2$rss, xlab = "Number of Variables", ylab = "RSS", type = "l")

#adjusted R^2 graph
plot(reg.summary2$adjr2, xlab = "Number of Variables",
     ylab = "Adjusted RSq", type = "l")
which.max(reg.summary2$adjr2)
## [1] 17
points(17, reg.summary2$adjr2[17], col = "red", cex = 2, pch=20)

#Cp graph
plot(reg.summary2$cp, xlab = "Number of Variables",
     ylab = "Cp", type = "l")
which.min(reg.summary2$cp)
## [1] 16
points(16, reg.summary2$cp[16], col = "red", cex = 2, pch=20)

#BIC graph
plot(reg.summary2$bic, xlab = "Number of Variables",
     ylab = "BIC", type = "l")
which.min(reg.summary2$bic)
## [1] 11
points(11, reg.summary2$bic[11], col = "red", cex = 2, pch=20)

reg.summary2$adjr2[11]
## [1] 0.759456

The 11 variable model has the lowest BIC and all other models have higher degrees of freedom. This 11 variable model is different from the 11 variable obtained through best subset selection. This 11 variable model obtained by forward stepwise selection captures 75.94% of the variation in diagnosis which is worse than best subset.

The main takeaway from the subset selection methods is that over half of the variables were not necessary to capture the majority of the variation in diagnosis. A more thorough analysis utilizing cross validation to estimate test error is necessary to determine which of these models performs the best but we use mathematical adjustments to performance metrics (adjusted R^2, Cp, and BIC) to determine this. All of these subset selection methods capture about 75% of the variation in diagnosis so we can expect to accurately classify an observation to as malignant or benign about 75% of the time when using less than half of the available predictors. This shows the power of a small number of the predictors in determining which cancers are malignant and can be used in practice. For example, doctors can look at the metrics first when they have diagnostic data on a tumor and expect to accurately determine if the tumor is malignant 75% of the time which is significant because doctors now only need to consider about 11 or 12 characteristics instead of 29 which is a great improvement!

Now, we determine how this model performs by calculating and estimate of the test error

#split data into training and test set
set.seed(1)
train <- sample(1:nrow(x), nrow(x) / 2)
test <- (-train)
y.test <- y[test]

#perform CV to determine optimal tuning parameter
set.seed(1)
cv.out <- cv.glmnet(x[train,], y[train], alpha = 0)
plot(cv.out)

This plot shows how the test error increases as lamda (the shrinkage penalty) increases. As this shrinkage penalty increases, ridge regression esimates approach 0 and the model eventually reduces to the null model with no predictors which explans why test error grows so sharply. If we have gradually have less and less predictors, then we will not be able to explain the variation in diagnosis and hence the test error will be very high.

#lambda that minimizes the test MSE
bestlam <- cv.out$lambda.min
bestlam
## [1] 0.03739526
#test MSE associated with this lambda
ridge.pred <- predict(ridge.mod, s=bestlam, newx = x[test,])

To evaluate how well the classification tree does on this data, we will estimate the test error

#Splitting the data (280 becuase it is approximately half of the observations)

plot(cv.fit$size, cv.fit$dev, type = "b")
plot(cv.fit$k, cv.fit$dev, type = "b")

These plots show that as the size increases to 8 terminal nodes, the error rate decreases and that as the value of the cost-complexity parameter increases, the error rate increases.

Now we prune the tree to have 7 terminal nodes because the trees with 7 and 8 terminal nodes have the same number of CV errors and a simpler model is often better.

prune.fit <- prune.misclass(tree.fit, best = 7)
plot(prune.fit)
text(prune.fit, pretty = 0)

#We will use predict() again to see how well this tree performs
tree.pred <- predict(prune.fit, testdata,
                     type = "class")
table(tree.pred, testdata$diagnosis)
##          
## tree.pred   0   1
##         0 162  21
##         1   7  99

162+99/289 = 0.9031 or 90.31% correctly predicted so this tree performs quite well on the test data.

Conclusion

Important Variables And Their Significance

Across various models, concave points, perimeter measurements were consistently significant. These are all measurements of tumor shape and irregularity (or lack thereof), which as key factors in distinguishing malignant tumors which often have irregular and pronounced concave points. Radius measurements, area measurements, and perimeter measurements were significant in many models and is crucial as these measurements relate to the size and spread of the tumor, with larger and irregularly shaped tumors more likely to be malignant. Texture measurements and smoothness measurements relate to the smoothenss or roughness of the tumor surface which can also be indicative of malignancy. Understanding which variables are most indicative of malignancy can aid in early diagnosis and treatment.

Best Performing Models

This study compares various models for classification focusing on their accuracy, sensitivty, and specificity in classifying tumors as malignant or benign. There were 2 models that performed well in particular: logistic regression and random forests. Logistic regression demonstrated classification accuracy, sensitivity, and apecificity, making it a relialbe model for distinguishing between benign and malignant tumors. Its strength lies in the ability to handle linear relationships between the predictors and the response. Random forest excels when dealing with non-linear relationships between the predictors and response; however, it risks overfitting. Since we do not know the true nature of the decision boundary it is good that we have models that deal well with a linear and non-linear decision boundary.

Clinical Implications

Integrating these models into diagnositc tools can significantly improve the accuracy of breat cancer diagnoses and lessening the strain on the health care system. Our models provide predictions accuracy above 90% and if this holds in the real world provides a novel approach to improving treatment outcomes and survival rates. The insights of these models can also inform clinicans about the agressiveness and other characteristics of the tumor which will lead to optimal treatment planning, beter patient outcomes, and more efficient healthcare delivery.
